Name: Sepsis Cases - Event Log
Short description: This real-life event log contains events of sepsis cases from a hospital. Sepsis is a life threatening condition typically caused by an infection. One case represents the pathway through the hospital.
Further keywords:: (machine) learning, (online process) monitoring, automation, healthcare, meta-learning, privacy preservation

Name: BPI 2017 - Offer Log
Short description: Contains data from a financial institute including all applications filed and their subsequent handling. There may be multiple offers per application. However, at most one of them should always be accepted.

Name: Road Traffic Fine Management Process (not BPI)
Short description: A real-life event log taken from an information system of the Italian police. The information system supports the management and handling of road traffic fines by a local police force in Italy.
Further keywords:: alarm-based prescriptive process monitoring, business process deviance, incremental process discovery, multi-perspective, ordering, remaining time prediction, variants, workflow net

Name: BPI 2011
Short description: Contains data from from a Dutch Academic Hospital. Each case is a patient of a Gynaecology department. The log contains information about when certain activities took place, which group performed the activity and so on.
Further keywords:: (compliance) monitoring, (machine) learning, deviant process instances detection, drift detection, explainable predictions, healthcare, outcome prediction, temporal logic

Name: BPI 2012
Short description: Contains the event log of an application process for a personal loan or overdraft within a global financing organization.
Further keywords:: (in)frequent patterns in process models, (machine) learning, automation, event-log sampling, explainable predictions, generilazation in process discovery, multi-perspective, next event prediction, privacy preservation, remaining time prediction, sequence model, sequence prediction, simulation, temporal logic

Name: BPI 2013 - Open Problems
Short description: Rabobank Group ICT implemented ITIL processes and tracked events such as changes and incidents

Name: BPI 2013 - Closed Problems
Short description: Rabobank Group ICT implemented ITIL processes and tracked events such as changes and incidents

Name: BPI 2013 - Incidents
Short description: The log contains events from an incident and problem management system called VINST.

Name: BPI 2014 - Incident Records
Short description: Rabobank Group ICT implemented ITIL processes and tracked events such as changes and incidents

Name: BPI 2014 - Interaction Records
Short description: Rabobank Group ICT implemented ITIL processes and tracked events such as changes and incidents

Name: BPI 2015 - Log 3
Short description: Provided by 5 Dutch municipalities. The data contains all building permit applications over a period of approx. 4 years (Municipality 3)

Name: BPI 2015 - Log 1
Short description: Provided by 5 Dutch municipalities. The data contains all building permit applications over a period of approx. 4 years (Municipality 1)

Name: BPI 2016 - Clicks Logged In
Short description: Contains clicks of users that are logged in from a Dutch autonomous administrative authority that implements employee insurances and provides labour market and data services.

Name: BPI 2017 - Application Log
Short description: Contains data from a financial institute including all applications filed and their subsequent handling. There may be multiple offers per application. However, at most one of them should always be accepted.
Further keywords:: (machine) learning, alarm-based prescriptive process monitoring, automation, privacy preservation, remaining time prediction, resource constraints, simulation, trace ordering

Name: BPI 2018
Short description: The process covers the handling of applications for EU direct payments for German farmers from the https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Agricultural_Guarantee_Fund. It contains yearly allocation of direct payments, starting with the application and, if all goes well, finishing with the authorization of a payment.

Name: BPI 2020 - Travel Permits
Short description: Contains 2 years of data from the reimbursement process at TU/e. Travel permits should be approved before making any arrangements.

Name: BPI 2019
Short description: Contains the purchase order handling process of a multinational company operating from the Netherlands in the area of coatings and paints.

Name: BPI 2020 - International Declarations
Short description: Contains 2 years of data from the reimbursement process at TU/e. For international trips, permission is needed from the supervisor.

Name: BPI 2020 - Domestic Declarations
Short description: Contains 2 years of data from the reimbursement process at TU/e. For domestic trips, no prior permission is needed, i.e. an employee can undertake these trips and ask for reimbursement of the costs afterwards.

Name: BPI 2020 - Prepaid Travel Cost
Short description: Contains 2 years of data from the reimbursement process at TU/e.

Name: Helpdesk
Short description: Ticketing management process of the Help desk of an Italian software company

Name: Receipt phase of an environmental permit application process (WABO), CoSeLoG project
Short description: Data originates from the CoSeLoG project where (dis)similarities between processes of different Dutch municipalities have been investigated. Here: execution of the receiving phase of the building permit application process.

Name: Environmental permit application process (‘WABO’), CoSeLoG project – Municipality 4
Short description: Data originates from the CoSeLoG project where (dis)similarities between processes of different Dutch municipalities have been investigated. Here: execution of a building permit application process in one of five anonymous municipalities (municipality 4)

Name: Environmental permit application process (‘WABO’), CoSeLoG project – Municipality 1
Short description: Data originates from the CoSeLoG project where (dis)similarities between processes of different Dutch municipalities have been investigated. Here: execution of a building permit application process in one of five anonymous municipalities (municipality 1)
